These practices are not only violations of the human rights of the individuals, but also an instrumentalist approach to sustain the status quo and the hierarchy of gender identities. Women living in poverty are particularly susceptible as they face high levels of structural violence, including difficulty accessing health and legal services needed to address the effects of interpersonal GBV.
Potential female leaders
Men have not been spared either. Reports indicate that men have also had their share of GBV through spousal verbal harassment, bodily harm and injury including their private parts being chopped off, denied food and other basic necessities.
Men have also been falsely accused of rape and attempted rape of their daughters or other girls, close female friends and relatives in order to settle scores.
At the work place, senior male officers have been falsely accused of enticing women sexually and have seen a backlash from women folk. Likewise junior male officers have been reprimanded for suggestive looks by their seniors. The worst bit is that authorities and community in general look down on men when they report such cases.



